{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-ad4eda759dd4e724", "type": "tool_result", "content": " X3-OPD: Distilling Reasoning into Large Audio-Language Models via On-Policy Alignment Report GitHub Issue × Title: Content selection saved. Describe the issue below: Description: Submit without GitHub Submit in GitHub arXiv is now an independent nonprofit! Learn more &times; Back to arXiv Why HTML? Report Issue Back to Abstract Download PDF Abstract 1 Introduction 2 Related Work 2.1 Reasoning in Large Audio Language Models 2.2 Knowledge Distillation for Large Language Models 3 Preliminaries 3.1 Problem Setting 3.2 Offline Distillation and its Limitation Perception–text divergence Exposure bias across modalities 4 Method 4.1 Three-Tier Symmetric Data Construction Tier 1: Textual reasoning rendered into speech. Tier 2: Audio reasoning grounded in captions. Tier 3: Spoken dialogue with prosody-aware captions. 4.2 Offline Warm-start 4.3 Cross-modal On-policy Distillation On-policy Multi-path Rollout. Cross-Modal Teacher Scoring. Cross-Modal Distillation Objective. 5 Experiments 5.1 Experimental Setup Backbones. Training data. Training configuration. Evaluation benchmarks. 5.2 Main Results Significant Enhancements in Cross-Modal Reasoning. Mitigating Perceptual Regression via On-Policy Distillation. Residual Gaps on Perceptual Axes. 5.3 CoT-quality Evaluation 5.4 Capability Preservation under Domain Shift 6 Conclusion References A Additional Experiment Details Training Setup and Hyperparameters. Implementation Details. B Baseline Descriptions B.1 Closed-Source LALMs GPT-4o-Audio (OpenAI, 2024 ) . Gemini-3-Flash (Comanici et al. , 2025 ) . B.2 Open-Weight LALMs Qwen2-Audio-Instruct (Xu et al. , 2025a ) . GLM-4-Voice (Zeng et al. , 2024 ) . Qwen2.5-Omni-7B (Xu et al. , 2025b ) . Qwen3-Omni-Instruct (Xu et al. , 2025c ) . Qwen3-Omni-Thinking (Xu et al. , 2025c ) . B.3 Reasoning-Specialized LALMs (Section 5.3 , Table 2 ) Audio-Reasoner (Xie et al. , 2025 ) . Step-Audio-R1 (Tian et al. , 2025 ) . C Ablation Study Contribution of individual data tiers. Impact of SFT warm-start duration. Exposure bias in full-corpus warm-starts. D Prompt Templates P1: Teacher chain-of-thought prompt (OPD stage). P2: Tier-1 spoken-style rewriting prompt. P3: Tier-2 caption reconstruction prompt. License: CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 arXiv:2607.21550v1 [cs.LG] 23 Jul 2026 X 3 -OPD: Distilling Reasoning into Large Audio-Language Models via On-Policy Alignment Dongjie Fu 1,2 , Di Cao 1 , Xize Cheng 2 , Zihan Zhang 2 , Wenxu Jia 2 , Yifu Chen 2 , Shengpeng Ji 1,2 , Yu Zhang 2 , Tao Jin 2 1 Tencent Hunyuan 2 Zhejiang University Corresponding author. Abstract While audio large language models have achieved remarkable progress in auditory perception, they still lag behind text-based large language models in deep logical reasoning capabilities. This performance disparity primarily stems from the scarcity of high-quality audio reasoning data. To bridge this modality gap, we propose a novel cross-modal on-policy distillation framework. Our approach leverages a powerful text model as a teacher to provide dynamic correction and guidance to the audio foundational model during on-policy exploration. Furthermore, we construct a three-tier symmetric dataset encompassing logical reasoning, complex audio reasoning, and speech dialogue. By dynamically aligning the student model’s reasoning trajectories within the high-noise auditory space with the teacher model’s prior knowledge in the clean text space, our method effectively distills robust reasoning capabilities into the audio domain. Extensive experiments demonstrate that our model achieves substantial improvements on the audio and speech understanding benchmarks, paving a new path for comprehensive audio-language understanding. X 3 -OPD: Distilling Reasoning into Large Audio-Language Models via On-Policy Alignment Dongjie Fu 1,2 , Di Cao 1 , Xize Cheng 2 , Zihan Zhang 2 , Wenxu Jia 2 , Yifu Chen 2 , Shengpeng Ji 1,2 , Yu Zhang 2 , Tao Jin 2 † † thanks: Corresponding author. 1 Tencent Hunyuan 2 Zhejiang University 1 Introduction Recent advances in Large Audio-Language Models (LALMs) mark a significant shift from the traditional cascaded paradigm of pairing Automatic Speech Recognition with text-only Large Language Models (LLMs) (Zhang et al. , 2023 ; Tang et al. , 2023 ; Xu et al. , 2025a ) . At the perceptual level, LALMs natively model continuous acoustic signals and thereby preserve paralinguistic and environmental cues, including intonation, emotion, speaker turns, and sound events, that are irreversibly lost in intermediate transcription. More fundamentally, this native interface also reshapes the reasoning paradigm: instead of inferring over a sanitized textual transcript, the model can ground its inferences directly in the acoustic signal, leveraging prosodic emphasis, ambient context, and temporally structured sound events that have no faithful textual surrogate (Xu et al. , 2025c ; Tian et al. , 2025 ) . In doing so, LALMs open a path toward comprehensive audio-language understanding, in which perception", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "29c5a6fb-eb9f-417d-82a5-6fe6a24f3989", "uuid": "a703ac53-28a6-4bcc-a27f-00ae57b47846", "timestamp": "2026-07-24T07:35:56.240Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": " X3-OPD: Distilling Reasoning into Large Audio-Language Models via On-Policy Alignment Report GitHub Issue × Title: Content selection saved. Describe the issue below: Description: Submit without GitHub Submit in GitHub arXiv is now an independent nonprofit! Learn more &times; Back to arXiv Why HTML? Report Issue Back to Abstract Download PDF Abstract 1 Introduction 2 Related Work 2.1 Reasoning in Large Audio Language Models 2.2 Knowledge Distillation for Large Language Models 3 Preliminaries 3.1 Problem Setting 3.2 Offline Distillation and its Limitation Perception–text divergence Exposure bias across modalities 4 Method 4.1